Great! Here's a simple implementation of a slime soccer game using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript:

HTML:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Slime Soccer</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div id="slime"></div>
  <div id="ball"></div>

  <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

CSS (style.css):
```css
body {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}

#slime {
  position: absolute;
  bottom: 10px;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, 0);
  width: 100px;
  height: 10px;
  background-color: green;
}

#ball {
  position: absolute;
  bottom: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, 50%);
  width: 20px;
  height: 20px;
  border-radius: 50%;
  background-color: red;
}
```

JavaScript (script.js):
```javascript
document.addEventListener("keydown", moveSlime);

function moveSlime(event) {
  const slime = document.getElementById("slime");
  const slimePosition = slime.offsetLeft;

  if (event.key === "ArrowLeft" && slimePosition > 0) {
    slime.style.left = slimePosition - 10 + "px";
  } else if (event.key === "ArrowRight" && slimePosition < window.innerWidth - slime.offsetWidth) {
    slime.style.left = slimePosition + 10 + "px";
  }
}
```

This code sets up a simple slime soccer game. The green div represents the slime and can be moved horizontally using the left and right arrow keys. The red div represents the ball in the center of the screen.

You can save the HTML code into an `index.html` file, the CSS code into a `style.css` file, and the JavaScript code into a `script.js` file in the same folder. Then open the `index.html` file in your web browser to play the game.

Please note that this is a basic implementation, and you can customize and enhance it further according to your requirements.

